    public interface ITagValueIterableFromTag<I extends Iterator<ITagValue>>
extends Iterable<ITagValue>
    Interface defining iteration over an underlying sequence of ITagValues.

    Implementations must guarantee:

    • That a new iterator is created on each call via this API
    • Access is provided to the underlying ITagValue elements such that changing their values changes the underlying data.
    • Structural modifications via the iterator (e.g. java.util.Iterator.remove()) are not supported.

    We extend the Iterable interface primarily so that implementations may be used in "foreach" context.

    Clients of this interface must not store ITagValue elements encountered during iteration. Rather, they should use ITagValue.copyFrom(ITagValue) to make a copy for storage if necessary.

    • Method Detail

      • iterator

        I iterator()
        Create an iterator over a collection of ITagValues.

        The following methods are not supported by the returned iterator:

        • java.util.ListIterator#remove()
        • java.util.ListIterator#add()
        • java.util.ListIterator#set()

        Calling any of them results in an UnsupportedOperationException.

        This method guarantees that a new iterator instance is returned with each call.

        The ITagValue objects returned are references to the underlying data, however, there are no guarantees regarding whether objects are created or not. Changing the values of these objects changes the underlying data. To avoid this behaviour you can use ITagValue.copyFrom(ITagValue) to copy the returned value before modifying it. If you intend on storing the returned ITagValue then copying it first is highly recommended.

        Specified by:
        iterator in interface Iterable<ITagValue>
        Returns:
        Iterator over ITagValues. Guaranteed to be a new instance for each call.

      • iterator

        I iterator(int tag)
        Create an iterator over a collection of ITagValues.

        This method has precisely the same semantics as iterator(), except that iteration commences at the first instance of a ITagValue which contains the specified tag (if any).

        Parameters:
        tag - The tag at which to start iteration. A tag ≤ 0 is considered out of range and implies the start of the collection. If multiple instances of this tag exist iteration commences at the first one.
        Returns:
        Iterator over ITagValues. Guaranteed to be a new iterator instance for each call.
        Throws:
        NoSuchElementException - If no ITagValue exists with the specified tag.
